title: Prostate Cancer Survivor, Advocate, Speaker
description: After being diagnosed with prostate cancer and trying to find answers to my questions and not finding much from doctors or the Internet, I was completely frustrated at the lack of information. I was invited to a prostate cancer symposium at the Moffitt Cancer Research Center and after listening to a doctor speak, I was picked out of the audience and asked to speak about my own cancer journey. Needless to say, this meeting was God ordained; a Baptist minister asked to speak at a gathering of people? As I told the doctor, I was geared to go an hour! After some humor, I did speak and I covered everything from soup to nuts, including the very personal things that had happened to me and that I knew had happened to every man in the audience. It was a topic that no one seems to want to talk about, including the medical world, doctors and nurses, no one says a word, and when I did, I think every hand in that room was in the air, wanting to talk more. After the meeting, I was asked to become a speaker on prostate cancer issues and that's what I have done. I have studied this disease and have learned some of the basics and I share from my heart the journey that my wife of 39 years and myself have been on. This isn't just my journey. It's our journey, and we have travel this road together, sharing the pain and loss of the sexual side of this disease. The questions isn't "If I will be affected" but when. The prostate is the most important gland in the male reproductive track and it's going to removed by surgery, or destroyed by radiation, freezing or by cooking it! As a man who had gone through this, each of us must find what will become our new "normal!" Sex will never be what it once was. Those years are gone forever, but, life can still be worth living and sex can still be satisfying but it will be different.
name: Dan Biser
